    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-07-14T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-07-14T05:00:00-05:00" n="128"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d128">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00R296/4467: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Belgium</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gibson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Brussels</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-07-14T11:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 14, 1931—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 14—9:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>81. Reference is made to my telegram No. 80, July 13, 11 p.m.<note n="72"
                        xml:id="d128fn72">Not printed.</note> Last night the Belgian Cabinet
                    decided, pending some German initiative toward direct negotiations, to withhold
                    action on proposals for notification of provisional postponement of German
                    payments and Belgian participation in the London Conference.</p>
                <p>Throughout this period we have been in close touch with the Belgian authorities
                    and it seems evident that three factors are contributing to this shortsighted
                    decision: (1) strong French pressure to bring the Government back to supporting
                    the French position; (2) a state of misgiving and lack of confidence resulting
                    from the reports of the Belgian Ambassador in Washington (I have been able to
                    counteract this on some individual points, but the minds of the Belgian
                    officials have undoubtedly been prejudiced); and (3) complete confusion of mind
                    as to what is happening in Germany and what the consequences will be for
                    Belgium.</p>
                <p>The British Embassy has had no success in its efforts to get a reply to its
                    invitation to the Belgians to attend the London Conference.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gibson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
